<scopecontent>
<head>Scope and Content of Collection</head>
<p>The Gordy Collection of Circus Photographs featured a wide array of images from mostly the 1900s to the 1940s, documenting circus life.  It focuses primarily on the Ringling Brothers Barnum and Bailey Circus, and shows not only animal and human performers, but features behind the scenes images that give a greater view into what was life for those who traveled with the group every year.</p>
<p>Most photographs contain no additional contextual information on the back.  However, this is not always the case and it is possible to determine a rough date range for the overall collection.</p>
<p>Prominent are photographs of circus animals, with the elephants taking up the most space. See arrangement note for additional details.</p>
</scopecontent>
<arrangement>
<head>Arrangement</head>
<p>Upon arrival, the Gordy Collection of Circus Photographs was divided into two groups.  The first, which compromises series I, featured a category based organizational system for photographs based on the image subject. This has been entirely kept intact.  </p>
<p>The second group was labeled as "circus miscellaneous."  While some materials was grouped together and labeled, such as a photo group of calliopes, most were not.  Material which was placed in a folder together has been kept together, and material that is recognizable by format, such as cartes de visite, has been kept together.  Otherwise these photographs remain in original order, pending review and additional context provided.</p>
</arrangement>
